Seen as the front runners in the hotly contested mini poll occasioned by the death of Senator Boniface Kabaka, the three faced off as they pulled huge crowds of supporters and long convoys of vehicles to escort them to IEBC’s county offices.
In an apparent show of political might, the candidates were each escorted by dozens of buses, trucks, cars and hundreds of bodabodas ferrying their supporters waving campaign caps and miniature flags.





The campaign teams staged peaceful road shows along Machakos town streets and addressed separate rallies, each exuding confidence that they will emerge victorious in the March 18 by-election.
The day climaxed with an emotional exchange between former Machakos Senator Johnstone Muthama and his estranged wife Agnes Kavindu–the Wiper candidate, who tore into each other over their bitter divorce that is likely to dominate the campaigns.
Mr Muthama publicly denounced his ex-wife at a rally at the Machakos Bus Park saying she doesn’t merit to represent Machakos County at the Senate. He was accompanied by several MPs and senators affiliated to Tangatanga wing of Jubilee party.
Referring her as “that other candidate”, Mr Muthama said his former spouse is the least qualified in the race and will perform poorly in debates and representation if elected to the Senate, prompting an immediate hard tackle from her.



