“Have you heard me insult my ex-husband anywhere since we separated? I can’t do that because I respect him as the father of my children and I ask you all to respect him, and keep our marital issues out of this campaign” she said amid cheers.
She was escorted to the IEBC offices by Wiper leader Kalonzo Musyoka, Amani National Congress leader Musalia Mudavadi, Ford Kenya leader Moses Wetangula, Kanu chairman and Baringo Senator Gideon Moi and several Wiper MPs.
Earlier in the day, Mr John Mutua Katuku, a former minister in the Kibaki regime who also served for two terms as the MP for Mwala constituency, addressed a similar crowds at Mulu Mutisya gardens, then proceeded to Masii, Wamunyu, Kithimani and Matuu markets, after he was cleared by IEBC.
Mr Katuku was accompanied by Machakos Governor Alfred Mutua, his deputy Francis Maliti, Yatta MP Charles Kilonzo and former Machakos Women Rep Dr Susan Musyoka and dozens of MCAs on the campaign trail.
The by-election is shaping into a three-horse race pitting Katuku, Kavindu and Ngengele but IEBC has cleared seven other candidates. Parties scramble to pick their best bets as disgruntled Ruto’s allies rejoin contest. Katuku is vying for the county’s senate seat on a Maendeleo Chap Chap ticket. DP Ruto accused of coming up with new pledges without fulfilling earlier promises. A spot check by Nation on Tuesday found no signs of the cross slab. BBI Bill to be tabled in all the counties after IEBC verified 1.14 million signatures.